tspan.tspan: Exploring the
coronavirus
phylogenetic tree built
using
spike
protein aminoacid sequences
Authors:
Wojciech Kretowicz
Szymon Maksymiuk
Kacper Siemaszko
Olaf Werner
The vast amount of data available for phylogenetic
tree construction, turned out to be more challenging
than convenient. The choice of coronavirus
sequences for building the phylogenetic trees had to
take into account its properties and hypotheses to
verify with the constructed visualization. As the
phylogenetic trees try to recreate the genealogy of
the sequenced coronavirus genomes, the final set
should be chosen from the similar period of time, as
comparing two chronologically distant sequences
does not contribute much information. The frequency
over time of the new genome sequences in four
countries, from which three have recorded significant
mutations of SARS-CoV-2 allowed us to choose the
period with the most information, which turned out to
be the first quarter of 2021.
The efforts against COVID-19 pandemic introduced the new
mRNA vaccine technology. The aim of these vaccines is to train
the patient’s immune system to recognize characteristic
coronavirus protein called spike protein. It is one of the proteins
found in each strain of SARS-CoV-2 (which consists of 25-29
proteins) and it is coded with the second longest amino acid
sequence.
The most common comparison made during the COVID-19
pandemic is the one between COVID-19 caused by SARS-CoV-2
and influenza, also known as the flu, caused by Influenza A virus.
There is a significant structural difference between the two, as
seen in the comparison plot above – SARS-CoV-2 genome
sequence is twice the length of the Influenza A. They also differ in
the number of coded proteins – the particular coronavirus
sequence consists of 27 proteins, with spike protein highlighted in
red, whereas the Influenza A consists of 8 segments coding 11
proteins.
The phylogenetic tree was made using a coronavirus spike protein sequences
from 4 countries – South Africa, Brasil, Poland and the United Kingdom – with 15
sequences from each. The main takeaway from the plot is the visible separation of
the South African strain, the Brasilian strain, and all the other sequences. The
results are aligned with the reportings of the South African and Brasilian strains’
immunity against the vaccine. As we can see, the spike protein sequence differs
mostly between these two strains and the sequences from other countries.
